<table align="center" width="900" cellspacing="1"  cellpadding="10" border="0" bgcolor="#FFFFF0">
<tr><td><div>

<font size="+4" color=#990000>Other irregular verbs</font> are only partially irregular.  They have normal endings
but undergo a small change in their stems.  These verbs are called <font color="#0A14C4"><strong>stem-changing verbs</strong></font>.<br>
<br>

Note how the "o" in "dormir" turns into "ue":<br>
<table align="center" cellpadding=10" bgcolor="#D7EBD7" width="100%" border=1>
<tr><td colspan=2 align=center><div><strong>Dormir (the "<font color="#0A14C4">o</font>" in the stem turns into 
"<font color="#0A14C4">ue</font>")</strong></div></td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor=#FFAFAF><div>yo d<font color="#0A14C4"><strong>ue</strong></font>rmo</div></td>

<td valign="bottom"><div>nosotros / nosotras dormimos</div></td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor=#FFAFAF><div>t&uacute; d<font color="#0A14C4"><strong>ue</strong></font>rmes</div></td>

<td valign="bottom"><div>vosotros / vosotras dorm&iacute;s</div></td></tr>

<tr>
<td valign="bottom" bgcolor=#FFAFAF><div>&eacute;l / ella / usted d<font color="#0A14C4"><strong>ue</strong></font>rme</div></td>

<td valign="bottom" bgcolor=#FFAFAF><div>ellos / ellas / ustedes d<font color="#0A14C4"><strong>ue</strong></font>rmen</div></td>
<br>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
Note that not all the forms change.  The pattern <font color="#0A14C4"><strong>looks like a boot</strong></font>.



</div></td></tr>







